  "prompt": "What does \"ride or die\" mean and where did it come from?",
  "response": "\"Ride or die\" is a slang term that refers to an extremely loyal person who will support their partner, friend, or group unconditionally, no matter the circumstances. It implies that someone would be willing to stay committed or even risk their own safety for someone else.\n\nThe phrase originated in hip-hop and African American culture in the 1990s, initially referring to romantic partners who would stick together through difficult times. It was popularized by rap and hip-hop artists and has since become a broader cultural expression of unwavering loyalty.\n\nThe term is thought to have roots in the idea of literally riding together and being willing to die alongside someone, metaphorically representing complete devotion and solidarity. Over time, it has expanded to describe close friendships, familial relationships, and other strong personal bonds.",
